  <page>
    <m>{\large \textbf{5.2 Worksheet Exercises}}</m> 
    <exercise workspace="1in">
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Let <m>A</m> be a <m>3 \times 4</m> matrix. What must <m>c</m> and <m>d</m> be if we define the linear transformation 
                <m>T : \mathbb{R}^c \to \mathbb{R}^d</m> by <m>T(\vec{x}) = A\vec{x}</m>?
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </exercise>
  </page>
  <page>
    <exercise workspace="1in">
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Let <m>T : \mathbb{R}^2 \to \mathbb{R}^2</m> be a linear transformation such that
            </p>
            <me>T {\begin{pmatrix}{\begin{bmatrix}x_1 \\ x_2 \end{bmatrix}} \end{pmatrix}} = x_1 {\begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}} + x_2 {\begin{bmatrix}4 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix}}</me>
        </introduction>
        <p>Construct a matrix <m>A</m> so that <m>T(\vec{x}) = A\vec{x}</m> for all vectors <m>\vec{x}</m>.</p>
    </exercise>
  </page>
  <page>
    <exercise workspace="1in">
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Let <m>T : \mathbb{R}^4 \to \mathbb{R}^3</m> be a linear transformation such that
            </p>
            <p><me>T {\begin{bmatrix}4 \\ 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}} = T {\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix}} \neq \vec{0}</me>.</p>
        </introduction>
        <p>Identify a non-trivial solution <m>\vec{x}</m> to <m>T\vec{x} = \vec{0}</m>.</p>
    </exercise>
  </page>
  <page>
    <exercise workspace="1in">
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Let <m>T_A</m> be the linear transformation with the matrix below. Match each choice of <m>A</m> on the the left with the geometric description of the action of <m>T_A</m> on the right.
            </p>
            <me>
            \begin{matrix}  
            {\begin{bmatrix} .5 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp .5 \end{bmatrix}}  \hskip1in    \amp   \hskip1in     \textup{rotation by }90^{\circ} \\
            {\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}}    \hskip1in    \amp   \hskip1in    \textup{A shear} \\
            {\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix}}    \hskip1in  \amp     \hskip1in    \textup{Projection onto }y\textup{ axis} \\
            {\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}}  \hskip1in      \amp    \hskip1in    \textup{dilation by }1/2
            \end{matrix}
            </me>
        </introduction>
    </exercise>
  </page>
  <page>
    <exercise workspace="1in">
        <introduction>
            <p>
               Indicate whether the statements are true or false.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <p>If <m>A</m> is a <m>3 \times 2</m> matrix then the map <m>x \mapsto Ax</m> cannot be one-to-one.</p>
        </task>
        <task>
            <p>If <m>A</m> is a <m>2 \times 3</m> matrix then the map <m>x \mapsto Ax</m> cannot be onto.</p>
        </task>
        <task>
            <p>The linear transform <m>T_A : \mathbb{R}^n \to \mathbb{R}^m</m> is one-to-one if and only if the only solution to <m>A\vec{x} = \vec{0}</m> is the trivial solution.</p>
        </task>
    </exercise>
  </page>
  <page>
    <exercise workspace="1in">
        <introduction>
            <p>
               Construct the standard matrix of the linear transformation <m>T</m>.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <p><m>T : \mathbb{R}^2 \to \mathbb{R}^4</m>, where <m>T \begin{pmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}1 \\ 0\end{bmatrix}\end{pmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1 \\ 4 \\ 1\end{bmatrix}
            </m> and <m>T\begin{pmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}\end{pmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}1 \\ 6 \\ 1 \\ 8\end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
        </task>
        <task>
            <p><m>T</m> is a vertical shear given by <m>T(\vec{e}_2) = 2\vec{e}_2</m> and <m>T(\vec{e}_1) = \vec{e}_1-2\vec{e}_2</m>.</p>
        </task>
        <task>
            <p>A matrix <m>A \in \mathbb{R}^{2 \times 2}</m> such that <m>T (\vec{x}) = A\vec{x}</m>. <m>T</m> is a linear transformation that first reflects vectors across the line <m>x_1 = x_2</m>, then rotates them counterclockwise by <m>\pi</m> radians about the origin, then reflects them across the line <m>x_2 = 0</m>.</p>
        </task>
    </exercise>
  </page>
